<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The previous Sunday was 26 May.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Winthrop Sargent (17531820), a son of Winthrop Sargent (17271793), the Continental prize agent at Gloucester, Mass., was a captain-lieutenant in Knoxs regiment of Continental artillery. After graduating from Harvard in 1771, Sargent traveled in Europe before joining Col. Richard Gridleys Massachusetts artillery regiment as a lieutenant in July 1775. He became a captain-lieutenant in Knoxs regiment the following December, and
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0423">[423]</span>
on 1 Jan. 1777 he was made a captain in the 3d Continental Artillery. From December 1779 to the end of the war Sargent served Gen. Robert Howe as an aide-de-camp, and in August 1783 Congress brevetted him a major (see General Orders, 30 Dec. 1779, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 24:52728). Appointed secretary of the Northwest Territory in 1787, Sargent moved to Marietta, Ohio, the next year. In 1791 he served as adjutant on Gen. Arthur St. Clairs expedition and was seriously wounded in St. Clairs defeat by the Miami Indians in November 1791.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0003">3</a>
  
   <p>Plan no. 1 is in the Jared Sparks Collection at Cornell University Library, Ithaca, N.Y. (<span title="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fg-03" class="figure warning">see figure 3</span>). Stirling is referring to Tethards Hill at Roa Hook located on the east side of the Hudson about three miles down the river from the site of Fort Montgomery. After passing through a narrow defile in the highlands to the north, the Hudson widens into Peekskill Bay below this point of land. Fort Independence, which was built on Tethards Hill in August 1776 apparently as a result of Stirlings recommendation, commanded the approaches to the bay including the mouth of Peekskill Creek (now Annsville Creek) and the landing for the town of Peekskill. Salisbury Island (now Iona Island) lies on the west side of the Hudson about halfway between Roa Hook and the mouth of Popolopen Creek where Fort Montgomery stood.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0004">4</a>
  
   <p>Plan no. 2 is also in the Jared Sparks Collection at Cornell University Library (<span title="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fg-04" class="figure warning">see figure 4</span>). This map was drawn by Thomas Palmer, one of the commissioners appointed by the provincial congress to oversee the fortification of the highlands. He and fellow commissioner Gilbert Livingston were supervising the building of Fort Montgomery at this time, while commissioners William Bedlow and Jonathan Lawrence were posted at Fort Constitution.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0005">5</a>
  
   <p>Fort Clinton was built across Popolopen Creek from Fort Montgomery in August of this year. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-05-02-0320" class="document">George Clinton to GW, 23 July</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-05-02-0345" class="document">GW to Clinton, 26 July 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>Embrasures are openings for cannon in a parapet, and merlons are higher portions of wall or breastwork between them.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0007">7</a>
  
   <p>Plan no. 3 is with the other two plans in the Jared Sparks Collection at Cornell University Library (<span title="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fg-05" class="figure warning">see figure 5</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0238" class="document">Henry Beekman Livingston to GW, 14</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0291" class="document">21 May 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>This return, which is signed by Col. Isaac Nicoll as commanding officer, shows that on 29 May the garrison at Fort Constitution consisted of 12 commissioned officers, 26 noncommissioned officers, and 152 privates, and the garrison at Fort Montgomery had 11 commissioned officers, 30 noncommissioned officers, and 188 privates. The strength of Capt. John Wisners company of minutemen was 4 commissioned officers, 10 noncommissioned officers, and 42 privates. Of the 41 guns fit for use at Fort Constitution, 31 were in the hands of Wisners minutemen. At Fort Montgomery there were only 22 guns fit for use. A total of 323 muskets were needed for the two garrisons (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>James Houmans undated return shows that Walter Livingston had deposited at the fort 57 barrels of flour, 133 barrels of pork, 66 bushels of peas,
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0424">[424]</span>
1 tierces of molasses, and  box of candles, while Abraham Livingston as of 30 May had laid in 20 barrels of flour, 23 barrels of pork, 16 barrels of beef, 45 bushels of peas, 3 tierces of molasses,  box of candles, 72 pounds of soap, 12 barrels of Indian meal, and 3 hogsheads of rum (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Peter Force, ed. &lt;i&gt;American Archives&lt;/i&gt;. 9 vols. Washington, D.C., 183753. ]">Force, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">American Archives</span></span>, 4th ser., 6:67576; this document is not in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). See also Nehemiah Carpenters return of provisions at Fort Montgomery, 31 May 1776, which was also enclosed with this letter (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>


   <p>Walter Livingston (17401797) of New York, a son of Robert Livingston, Jr., the third lord of Livingston Manor, was appointed commissary of stores and provisions for the New York department on 17 July 1775 by the Continental Congress. At that time Congress did not anticipate that the main army would eventually move to New York, and the arrival of commissary general Joseph Trumbull in the colony from Boston this spring created much confusion about Livingstons duties and powers. Livingston and his patron General Schuyler, whose niece Cornelia was married to Livingston, wanted to maintain an independent role for Livingston at Albany because they feared that Trumbull, a native of Connecticut, would replace Livingston with Connecticut commissary Elisha Avery, Livingstons bitter rival of recent months. Congress settled the dispute on 8 July 1776 by resolving that the commissary general [Trumbull] have full power to supply both armies, that upon the lakes as well as that at New York; and also to appoint and employ such persons under him, and to remove any deputy commissary, as he shall judge proper and expedient; it being absolutely necessary, that the supply of both armies should be under one direction (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 5:527; see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-05-02-0197" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 11 July 1776</a>). That resolution prompted Livingston to resign his office in September 1776. He served in the New York general assembly 177779 and was speaker of the house part of that time. In 1782 Livingston was associated with Comfort Sands &amp; Co., contractors for supplying the army with provisions, and in 1784 he served in the Continental Congress.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>Stirling enclosed three payrolls for the civilians employed at the two forts, all dated 31 May. One of them lists the fifteen persons at Fort Constitution who are described in this paragraph, giving the total of their monthly wages as 104.3.4. Another payroll, signed by William Bedlow, one of the commissioners at Fort Constitution, lists seventeen employees at that fort, omitting an attendant and adding three seamen and 1 Sloop in the Service of Both forts for a total monthly cost of 138.10. The accuracy of this second payroll is supported by a return of the superintendents and laborers at Fort Constitution that Stirling also enclosed. Dated 31 May and signed by Bedlow, it lists the same personnel who appear in the second payroll and identifies the sloop as the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Liberty</span>, Henry Palmer, master. The third payroll covers the twenty-two employees at Fort Montgomery, whose monthly wages totaled 209. They are also listed in a return of personnel and implements at the fort dated 31 May and signed by commissioners Thomas Palmer and Gilbert Livingston. All five of the above-mentioned documents are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0012-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0012">12</a>

   <p>Stirling enclosed two copies of a list containing the names of twelve Loyalists from Dutchess County and one from Westchester County who were at Fort Montgomery on 31 May (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0425">[425]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0013-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0336-fn-0013">13</a>

   <p>Capt. Winthrop Sargents returns of the ordnance and ordnance stores at Fort Constitution on 30 May and at Fort Montgomery on 31 May indicate that there were six 32-pound iron cannon at Fort Montgomery and 77 iron cannon ranging in size from 1 to 9 pounds at Fort Constitution (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). Stirling also enclosed an account of artillery stores signed by Col. Isaac Nicoll that reports 43 mounted and 36 unmounted cannon, a total of 79, at Fort Constitution on 29 May, six 32-pounders at Fort Montgomery on that same date, and seven 6-pounders at New Windsor (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
